## Step 1 — open the cycle (this IS resume)

Read `.claude/team-forge/{{team}}/TASKS.yaml` (the `queue` + `gates`) and `tracker/status.json`.

- Stamp `current_cycle_id` (e.g. `cycle-<date>-NNN`) and `cycle_box_deadline` from the box.
- **Carry-over:** any item left `in_review` from a prior cycle re-attaches first (read it from
  `status.json.tickets[]`), before new triage.
- Log `cycle_started`; refresh the dashboard (see **Observability**).

> **Staleness check.** This launcher + `gen_dashboard.py` are baked from forge time. If the team-forge
> templates moved since, run `tools/forge.py --check .claude/team-forge/{{team}}/design.yaml`; on drift,
> `--resync` regenerates the template-derived files and preserves your ledger + artifacts.

## Step 2 — triage the queue

1. Run the `queue.eligibility` query → the eligible item set.
2. Apply `queue.triage`: classify each item, detect risk, set per-item `route` +
   `blast_radius` + `gate_set` (from the gate vocabulary). Write the partition to
   `status.json.tickets[]` and the `queue_*` counts. Log `ticket_triaged` / `ticket_routed`.
3. **`full-drain`** items proceed to Step 3. **`plan-gate`** items are the risky set — in an
   unattended cycle they **HOLD** (auto-approve nothing); surface them for human approval.

## Step 3 — drain in waves (the Workflow tool's `pipeline()`)

Draining a multi-item wave is a genuine N-way fan-out, so it **must** run on the **Workflow tool** —
call `pipeline(items, drain, gate)`, each item independently. Invoking this launcher is your
authorization to trigger it (no need to re-ask); the run is monitorable via `/workflows`. Do NOT
silently degrade to a sequential for-loop of inline dispatches — that loses the wave concurrency and
the run won't appear in `/workflows`.

**Single-item wave → inline.** If triage leaves only ONE eligible item, skip the Workflow burst and
drain it inline (one worker dispatch) — a pipeline of one is pure overhead. Two or more independent
items → the Workflow pipeline. Drain in waves of ≤ **{{WAVE_SIZE}}**, each item independently:
- **drain** — dispatch the **worker** profile (`{{team}}-worker`, own worktree) per item with a
  **scoped brief**: the item + the exact artifacts to read, not "go read the KB". The worker keeps
  its own **native persistent memory** across dispatches (`.claude/agent-memory/{{team}}-worker/`), so
  it carries forward what earlier items taught it — nothing for you to harvest. {{ESCALATION_NOTE}} On a provider-unavailable failure, retry one
  model tier down (e.g. fable → opus) before marking it blocked.
  - **Self-modifying item guard:** an item that edits `.claude/agents/**`, `.claude/skills/**`, hooks,
    or `settings.json` **cannot** be worker-drained — an in-session subagent races the config this
    session loaded. Pull it from the wave, mark it `blocked_on: fresh_session_handoff`, and hand it to a
    freshly-launched full-permission session (like a sequential `fresh_session` task); drain the rest.
- **gate** — run the item's `gate_set` (mandatory under unattended; never PR on red).
- on green → open a PR against `{{integration_branch}}`; set the item `stage: pr_ready`.

The items are independent — no peer coordination. The lead owns the wave dispatch and the ledger.

**Worktree boundary — never edit a live worker's tree.** A dispatched worker owns its worktree
for the life of the dispatch. Do **not** edit, commit, or push inside it while that worker is
active — from inside a worktree, *your* edits are indistinguishable from a hostile third party:
the worker sees files change under it, resets them, sees them change again, and reasonably
escalates (a real run had a worker file a false "rogue agent" GitHub issue over exactly this).
When a code review lands findings on a worker's branch, **route them back to the worker** as a
follow-up dispatch — do not grab the wheel. If you genuinely must take over, first tell the
worker to **stand down and wait for it to confirm** before you touch the tree.

**Box freeze:** past `cycle_box_deadline`, dispatch **no new** item/wave. An in-flight item
finishes its **current** iteration, checkpoints its PR, and carries as `in_review` to the next
cycle (NOT blocked, NOT done). Log `cycle_box_hit`.

## Step 4 — report + persist (+ rotate)

Update `status.json` (thin): per-item `stage` / `pr_url` / `gate_status`, the `queue_*`
counts, `budget`. (Each drained worker records its own cross-cycle learnings in its native agent
memory — nothing for you to harvest.) Refresh the dashboard (see **Observability**). Write a short
cycle report under `artifacts/<cycle-id>/`. **Rotate:** archive this cycle's detail to
`runtime/<cycle-id>/`; keep the live `status.json` to the current cycle. Log `cycle_completed`.

## Re-plan (W7)

If the routing predicate or gate vocabulary proves wrong mid-cycle, re-cut them in `TASKS.yaml`
(new plan version + one-line *why*; `current_plan` ← new path, append to `plan_history`, log
`replanned`) before continuing.

## Memory authority (single-writer)

You own `status.json` (thin) + `runtime/` + `artifacts/`. Workers write only their worktrees and
self-curate their **own** native persistent memory (`.claude/agent-memory/{{team}}-worker/`,
auto-managed by Claude Code) — that is the agent's, not yours. The dashboard is refreshed per
**Observability** (the render step, or a monitor teammate if configured).

## Naming discipline (IDs stay internal)

Item/ticket IDs are **internal-ledger-only** (`status.json`, `TASKS.yaml`). PR titles, commit
messages, and code comments describe the item in human terms, never by ID. Cycle report files are
content-descriptive **+ dated** (`<subject>-<YYYY-MM-DD>.md`) so successive cycle reports stay
distinguishable; fixed-name contracts (`status.json`, `TASKS.yaml`) are exempt. If an ID is needed on a
durable surface, carry a glossary.

